mfd: simple-mfd-i2c: register the spacemit-p1-reboot cell

The SpacemiT P1 PMIC is the only thing on the BPI-F3 that can actually
reset (or power off) the SoC from Linux: the vendor OpenSBI does not
implement the SBI System-Reset (SRST) extension (the kernel logs only
the IPI + RFENCE extensions at boot), so `reboot`/`poweroff` have no
firmware path and just hang at "reboot: Restarting system".

The kernel already ships the PMIC reset driver
(drivers/power/reset/spacemit-p1-reboot.c, POWER_RESET_SPACEMIT_P1=y),
which registers restart + power-off handlers that poke PWR_CTRL2 on the
P1. But it binds to a "spacemit-p1-reboot" platform device, and the MFD
core (simple-mfd-i2c) only registers the regulator and rtc cells for
"spacemit,p1" — so the driver never probes and no handler is installed.

Register the reboot cell so the driver binds. With this, `reboot` and
`poweroff` work via the PMIC (a real cold reset), which is essential for
operating the board remotely. Upstream-shaped; can be dropped once the
cell list is fixed in a newer kernel.

--- a/drivers/mfd/simple-mfd-i2c.c
+++ b/drivers/mfd/simple-mfd-i2c.c
@@ -107,6 +107,7 @@
 static const struct mfd_cell spacemit_p1_cells[] = {
 	{ .name = "spacemit-p1-regulator", },
 	{ .name = "spacemit-p1-rtc", },
+	{ .name = "spacemit-p1-reboot", },
 };

 static const struct simple_mfd_data spacemit_p1 = {
